# SNMP & LDAP Enumeration — Cheat Sheet

Quick reference. Authorized targets only. Each line is `command` → what it does.
Example IPs: SNMP host `192.168.1.50`, DC `192.168.1.10`, domain `corp.local`, user `jdoe:Spring2024`.

---

## SNMP (UDP 161)

### Discover
```bash
nmap -sU -p 161 --open 192.168.1.0/24      # UDP scan: find hosts with port 161 open
onesixtyone 192.168.1.0/24 public          # fast sweep: find agents answering to "public"
```

### Find community string
```bash
printf 'public\nprivate\nmanager\n' > community.txt   # build a wordlist
onesixtyone -c community.txt 192.168.1.50             # try each string against the host
```

### Read data (needs a valid community)
```bash
snmpwalk -v 2c -c public 192.168.1.50                 # walk the whole MIB tree (everything readable)
snmp-check 192.168.1.50 -c public                     # same data, formatted into clean sections
```

### Targeted OID walks
```bash
snmpwalk -v 2c -c public 192.168.1.50 1.3.6.1.4.1.77.1.2.25   # local Windows usernames
snmpwalk -v 2c -c public 192.168.1.50 1.3.6.1.2.1.25.4.2.1.2  # running processes
snmpwalk -v 2c -c public 192.168.1.50 1.3.6.1.2.1.25.6.3.1.2  # installed software (+ versions)
```

### Flags
```
-sU        UDP scan (SNMP is UDP)        -v 2c   SNMP version 2c
-p 161     port 161 only                 -c      community string
--open     show only open ports          -c file (onesixtyone) wordlist of strings
```

**Findings → next:** open 161 → valid community → host profile → user list → version-based weaknesses.
**RW community (e.g. `private`) = critical finding.** Report it; don't issue writes without explicit scope.

